'''Scott Philip Brown''' (born September 12, 1959), an American politician, is the junior [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[Massachusetts]]. Brown is a member of the [[Republican Party of the United States|Republican Party]]. He previously served as a member of the [[Massachusetts General Court]], first in the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|State House of Representatives]] (1998<U+2013>2004) and then in the [[Massachusetts Senate|State Senate]] (2004<U+2013>2010).

Brown faced the [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic]] candidate, Massachusetts Attorney General [[Martha Coakley]], in the [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|2010 special election]] to succeed U.S. Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]. While initially trailing Coakley in polling by a large margin, Brown closed the gap in the first weeks of January 2010 before going on to win the election. Brown became the first Republican elected to the U.S. Senate from Massachusetts since [[Edward Brooke]] in 1972.<ref name="elec1">{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/senate/scott-brown-wins-massachusetts-senate-race.html|title=Scott Brown wins Massachusetts Senate special election race|work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 19, 2010}}</ref>

Prior to entering the state legislature, he had experience as a town [[Board of Selectmen|selectman]] and assessor. He is a practicing [[Attorneys in the United States|attorney]], concentrating in [[Property law|real estate law]] and serving as defense counsel in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]] of the [[Massachusetts Army National Guard]]. Brown is a graduate of [[Wakefield High School (Wakefield, Massachusetts)|Wakefield High School]] (1977), [[Tufts University]] (1981), and [[Boston College Law School]] (1985).

==Early life and education==
Brown was born on September 12, 1959 in [[Kittery, Maine]]<ref name="2007 Public Officers">{{cite web|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/publicofficersof20072008bost#page/46/mode/2up|title= 2007-2008 Public Officers of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts|first=William F.|last=Welch|coauthors= James, Steven T.}}</ref> and grew up in [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]].<ref name="dog">{{cite news|last=Mooney|first=Brian C.|date=November 20, 2009|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2009/11/20/being_the_underdog_never_deters_a_driven_brown/?page=full|title=Being the underdog never deters a driven Brown |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref> He often spent his summers in [[Newburyport, Massachusetts]], where his father served as a [[city council]]or for 18 years. Brown's father, Claude Bruce Brown, and mother, Judith,<ref name="odds-1718">{{cite book |author=Brown, Scott |date=2011 |title=Against All Odds: My Life of Hardship, Fast Breaks, and Second Chances |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |isbn=978-0062015549 |pages=17<U+2013>18}}</ref> divorced when he was about a year old. Both his parents have since remarried three times. His father and his grandfather were Republicans. His father has said that young Scott became interested in running for political office in the mid 1960s while accompanying him on a campaign for state office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newburyportnews.com/punews/local_story_014234708.html|title=Brown's dad proud of son's political rise|first=Katie|last=Katzman|date=January 15, 2010|publisher=Newbury Port News}}</ref> Scott Brown recalls holding campaign signs for his father.<ref name="live" />

Brown had a difficult childhood; after her divorce his working mother received [[welfare]] benefits.<ref name="oped">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2010/01/14/a_new_day_is_coming_restore_faith_and_balance/ |title=A New Day Is Coming To Restore Faith And Balance|last=Brown|first=Scott|date=January 14, 2010|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Brown experienced [[sexual abuse]] from a [[camp counselor]] who threatened to kill the ten-year-old boy if he told anyone&mdash;which he did not disclose even to his family until his autobiography ''Against All Odds'' (2011)<ref name="stahl20110220">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/02/20/60minutes/main20032276.shtml | title=The resilient Senator Scott Brown | accessdate=2011-02-23 | author=Stahl, Leslie | date=2011-02-20 | publisher=CBS News}}</ref><U+2014>and physical abuse from his stepfathers.{{r|arsenault20110217}} During various periods of his childhood, Brown lived with his grandparents and his aunt. He shoplifted many times,{{r|arsenault20110217}} and was arrested for stealing record albums and brought before Judge [[Samuel Zoll]] in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] at the age of 13 or 14.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/02/23/for_brown_second_chance_was_a_life_changing_moment/ |title=For Brown, second chance was a life-changing moment |first=Donovan |last=Slack |date=February 23, 2011 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Zoll asked Brown if his siblings would like seeing him play basketball in jail and required Brown to write a 1,500-word essay on that question as his punishment. Brown later said, "that was the last time I ever stole."<ref name="dog" />

He graduated from [[Wakefield High School (Wakefield, Massachusetts)|Wakefield High School]] in 1977.<ref name="bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.scottbrown.com/Bio.htm|title=About State Senator Scott Brown|publisher=Scott Brown|accessdate=January 21, 2010 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080527023111/http://www.scottbrown.com/Bio.htm |archivedate = May 27, 2008}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelors of Arts]] in History,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enews.tufts.edu/stories/1618/2010/01/19/ScottBrown |title=Tufts Alum Wins U.S. Senate Bid |publisher=Tufts University |date= |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> [[cum laude]] from [[Tufts University]] in 1981 and a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Boston College Law School]] in 1985. During his undergraduate career at Tufts, Brown was a member of the Kappa Chapter of [[Zeta Psi]] International Fraternity.<ref name="2007 Public Officers" /><ref name="glance">{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[The Washington Post]] |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/16/AR2010011600851.html|title=US Senate candidate Scott Brown, at a glance|date=January 16, 2010|accessdate=January 16, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>

==Non-political career==
===Army National Guard service===
Brown has said the rescue efforts of [[Army National Guard]] during the [[Northeastern United States blizzard of 1978]] impressed him. He joined the [[Massachusetts Army National Guard]] when he was 19, receiving his basic training at [[Fort Dix, New Jersey]],<ref name="dog" /> and attending [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] (ROTC) classes at the campus of [[Northeastern University]].<ref name="key">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/07/guard_service_a_key_to_candidate_brown/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=January 16, 2010|title=Guard service a key to candidate Brown|first=Brian C.|last=Mooney}}</ref> He was trained in [[Infantry Branch (United States)|infantry]], [[Quartermaster Corps (United States Army)|quartermaster]], and [[airborne forces|airborne]] duties, and in 1994 he joined the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps]] (JAG).<ref name="key" /> He has been active in the Guard for about 30 years and has risen to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]]. As the Army Guard's head [[defense attorney]] in [[New England]], Brown defended Guard members who had disciplinary difficulties such as positive [[drug tests]],<ref name="live" /> and provided [[estate planning]] and [[real estate]] advice to those who are about to deploy to war zones.<ref name="key" /> Brown has not served in [[Iraq]] or [[Afghanistan]], but said in 2009 that he was prepared to go if called. "I go where they order me to go... I'm just proud to serve and be part of the team."<ref name="live" /> He spent ten days to two weeks with the Guard in [[Kazakhstan]] and a week in [[Paraguay]].<ref name="live" />

He was awarded the Army [[Commendation Medal]] for meritorious service in [[homeland security]] shortly after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name="bio" /> He credits his military experience with causing him to focus on [[veteran]]'s issues as well as issues of war and peace.<ref name="live" /> He has served on the Veterans and Federal Affairs Committee, the Hidden Wounds of War Commission, and the Governor's Task Force on Returning Veterans during his career as a legislator.<ref name="live" />

===Modeling===
In June 1982, Brown, then a 22-year-old law student at Boston College, won ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' magazine's "America's Sexiest Man" contest. After two weeks on a [[crash diet]] of "three cans of tuna a day" and intensive workouts<ref name="arsenault20110217">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2011/02/17/brown_describes_childhood_of_beatings_sexual_abuse/?page=full|title=Brown describes beatings, sexual abuse in childhood|date=2011-02-17|first=Mark and Christopher Rowland|last=Arsenault|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> he was featured in the magazine's [[centerfold]], posing [[nude]] but strategically positioned so that according to Brown, "You don't see anything". In the accompanying interview, he referred to himself as "a bit of a patriot" and stated that he had political ambitions. The ''Cosmopolitan'' appearance and its $1,000 fee<ref name="live" /><ref name="guardian 01-20-10">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/jan/20/scott-brown-massachusetts-senator|title=Scott Brown: From Cosmo centrefold to Massachusetts senator|work=World news|date=January 20, 2010|first=James|last=Meikle|work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London}}</ref><ref name="Cosmo">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/scott-brown-nude-in-cosmo|title=Senator Is the Centerfold|author=Ashley Womble|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|date=September 22, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> helped pay for law school, and began for Brown a "long, lucrative" part-time catalog and print modeling career in New York and Boston during the 1980s.<ref name="bruni20100228" />

==Early political career==
Brown "caught the political bug" in 1992 when he was elected property [[assessor (property)|assessor]] of [[Wrentham, Massachusetts]].<ref name="live" /> In 1995, he was elected to the Wrentham [[Board of Selectmen]]. 

He successfully ran for the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] in 1998, representing the 9th Norfolk District for three terms. Brown again moved up the ladder of state politics to the state Senate in March 2004 when he won a special election to replace Democrat [[Cheryl Jacques]]. Brown was re-elected for a full term in November 2004, and again in November 2006, running without opposition the second time. He won re-election in November 2008, defeating Democratic candidate Sara Orozco by a 59<U+2013>41 percent margin. Following his re-election, Brown was one of five Republicans in the 40-seat Massachusetts senate. In the Massachusetts Senate, Brown served on committees dealing with consumer protection, professional licensing, education, election laws, public safety, and veterans' affairs.<ref name="glance" />

In February 2007, a controversy arose after Brown's appearance at [[King Philip Regional High School]] in [[Wrentham, Massachusetts]] as part of a debate on [[gay marriage]]. The high school students had launched a [[Facebook]] group attack on Brown and had made a derogatory remark about his daughter, [[Ayla Brown|Ayla]]. During his presentation, Brown defended himself and his daughter by directly quoting several vulgar statements they had made and announcing the names of the students who had written the statements. Critics questioned whether Brown should have quoted the profane comments in front of a high school audience.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/homepage/8998943093096972286|title=Brown on hot seat after quoting 'F' word at school appearance|author=Heather McCarron|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]] |date=February 10, 2007}}</ref>

''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that during six terms in the Legislature, three each in the House and Senate, Brown has a modest record of legislative initiatives, but he has carved out a niche as a leading advocate for [[veterans]]. [[Richard R. Tisei]] of [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]], the leader of the Republican minority in the state Senate, called Brown "the acknowledged expert on veterans' issues."<ref name="www.boston.com">[http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/07/guard_service_a_key_to_candidate_brown/ "Guard Service a Key to Candidate Brown"] ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' January 7, 2010</ref> State Senator [[Jack Hart (state senator)|Jack Hart]], a Democrat of [[South Boston]], said: "He does his homework, he's comprehensive in his approach, and on veterans' issues, he's one of them and has done a very good job on their behalf."<ref name="www.boston.com" />

As a legislator, Brown lists among his achievements his authorship of a 2007 law that created a check-off box on state income tax forms for veterans to indicate whether they served in Iraq or Afghanistan. The state uses the information to notify veterans of available services and benefits, including the Welcome Home Bonus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mass.gov/?pageID=veteransterminal&L=2&L0=Home&L1=Returning+Veterans&sid=Eveterans&b=terminalcontent&f=bonuses_gwot&csid=Eveterans |title=Welcome Home Bonus |publisher=Mass.gov |date=2001-09-11 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> that provides $1,000 for those returning from active duty in Afghanistan or Iraq.<ref name="www.boston.com" />

==U.S. Senate==
===2010 election===
{{Main|United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010}}
[[Image:Scott P. Brown.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Brown on the campaign trail.]]
On September 12, 2009, Brown announced his run for the U.S. Senate seat that became vacant with the death of [[Ted Kennedy]], saying the state "needs an independent thinker."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/world_us/20100121_Scott_Brown_proudly_proclaims_he_s__a_new_breed_of_Republican_.html|title=Scott Brown proudly proclaims he's 'a new breed of Republican'|first=Steve|last=Leblanc|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 21, 2010|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/jan/20/massachusetts-election-scott-brown|title='I'm Scott Brown. I'm from Wrentham. I drive a truck'|first=Oliver|last=Burkeham|date=January 21, 2010|work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London}}</ref>  ''Washington Post'' columnist [[Kathleen Parker]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Mooney| first=Alexander|title=Palin should step down, conservative commentator says|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/09/26/palin-should-step-down-conservative-commentator-says/ |work=[[CNN]] |date=September 26, 2008|accessdate=January 26, 2009}}</ref> said that Brown's political positions did not fall neatly into party lines, and called Brown "mainstream in a nation that defines itself as mostly conservative".<ref>{{Citation|last=Parker|first=Kathleen|author-link=Kathleen Parker|title=A Republican Senate upset in Massachusetts?|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 10, 2010|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/08/AR2010010803591.html|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref> Boris Shor, political scientist at the [[Harris School of Public Policy]], described Brown as a liberal Republican by national standards, but well-suited for his Massachusetts constituency. Shor explained the support Brown was receiving from the conservative national GOP as due to their "decentralized decision" to support the candidate most likely to win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bshor.wordpress.com/2010/01/15/scott-brown-is-a-more-liberal-republican-than-dede-scozzafava|title=Scott Brown is a more liberal Republican than Dede Scozzafava|first=Boris|last=Shor|date=January 15, 2010|accessdate=January 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2010/01/scott-brown-is-liberal-republican.html|title=Scott Brown is a Liberal Republican|date=January 15, 2010|accessdate=January 16, 2010|work=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|first=Andrew|last=Gelman|authorlink=Andrew Gelman}}</ref>

Brown won a landslide victory in the Republican primary on December 8, 2009, defeating late entrant and [[perennial candidate]] [[Jack E. Robinson III|Jack E. Robinson]] by a margin of 89 percent to 11 percent.<ref name="guardian 12-09-09">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/feedarticle/8848591|title=Kennedy special election puts GOP in spotlight|last=Johnson|first=Glenn|date=December 9, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London}}</ref>

Brown's opponents in the general election were Democratic nominee, Attorney General Martha Coakley, and [[independent (politician)|independent]] [[Joseph L. Kennedy]] (no relation to the [[Kennedy family]]). At the outset, he faced overwhelming odds because he was relatively unknown compared to Coakley, he was running as a Republican in a very Democratic state, and much of his campaigning had to be done during the Christmas and New Year's season when citizens do not generally pay much attention to politics.<ref name="Globe 12-08-09">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2009/12/scott_brown_win.html|title=Scott Brown wins GOP primary, readies for race against Coakley|first=Michael|last=Levenson|date=December 8, 2009|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> He polled far behind Coakley for several months, but closed the gap in the early weeks of January.<ref name="myfox 1-18-10">{{cite news|url=http://www.myfoxboston.com/dpp/news/politics/local_politics/poll-scott-brown-surges-to-double-digit-lead-over-martha-coakley|date=January 18, 2010|title=Poll: Scott Brown surges to double-digit lead over Martha Coakley|publisher=My Fox Boston}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/pdf/PPP_Release_MA_45398436.pdf|title=Senate Race Competitive|date=January 9, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2010|publisher=[[Public Policy Polling]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidemedford.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/ma-senate-poll-results.pdf|title=Senate poll results}}</ref><ref name="parker">{{cite news|work=[[The Washington Post]] |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/08/AR2010010803591.html|title=A Republican Senate upset in Massachusetts?|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2010|authorlink=Kathleen Parker|first=Kathleen|last=Parker}}</ref>

A week before the general election, Brown raised $1.3 million from over 16,000 donors in a 24-hour [[money bomb]]. His campaign office stated it raised $5 million over the period from January 11<U+2013>15.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/politics/view/20100112scott_brown_claims_13_million_in_late_senate_donations/ |title=Candidates for Kennedy seat make final money pitch|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 12, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2010|work=[[Boston Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/15/AR2010011504069.html|work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=January 16, 2010|title=Democrats scramble in Massachusetts to retain Ted Kennedy's old Senate seat|date=January 16, 2010|author1=Karl Vick|author2=Chris Cillizza}}</ref>  Charlie Cook of the ''[[Cook Political Report]]'' stated on January 17 that he would put his "finger on the scale" for Scott Brown as the favorite. The Rothenberg Political Report released a statement that "the combination of public and private survey research and anecdotal information now strongly suggests that Republican Scott Brown will defeat Democrat Martha Coakley in tomorrow's race".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/01/18/bay-state-battle-new-indicators-show-brown-gaining-ground/ |title=Bay State Battle: New Indicators Show Brown Gaining Ground|first=Mary Lu|last=Carnevale|date=January 18, 2010|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> [[Suffolk University]]'s polling of three [[bellwether]] counties on January 18 had Brown leading Coakley by double-digit margins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0110/31621.html|title=New Poll: Brown Up 9|first=David|last=Catanese|date=January 18, 2010|publisher=Politico}}</ref> Brown won the January 19 election, performing well in traditional Republican strongholds and holding rival Coakley's margins down in many Democratic precincts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2010/by_county/MA_US_Senate_0119.html?SITE=AP&SECTION=POLITICS|title=Massachusetts County Vote Results U.S. Senate&nbsp;<U+2013> Unexpired Term&nbsp;<U+2013> Special General|work=Associated Press |date=January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/01/19/massachusetts.senate/index.html |first=Jim|last=Acosta|coauthors= Bash, Dana|title=Brown wins Massachusetts Senate race|work=[[CNN]] |date=January 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/01/19/polls-close-competitive-massachusetts-senate-race/ |title=Brown Scores Upset Victory Over Coakley in Massachusetts Senate Race|publisher=FOX News|date=January 19, 2010|accessdate=January 19, 2010}}</ref>

[[Image:Senator Scott Brown 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Brown driving what during the campaign became his famous truck]]
One week before the January special election, a controversy arose over a Coakley approved television ad.  The ad referenced the [[conscientious objector]] amendment Brown had sponsored for inclusion in a 2005 proposed state measure on patients' rights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2006/02/15/state_orders_wal_mart_to_sell_morning_after_pill/ |title=State orders Wal-Mart to sell morning-after pill, Retailer says it will consider stocking drug at all US stores|first=Bruce|last= Mohl|date=February 15, 2006|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>  This amendment would have allowed individual healthcare workers and hospitals to refuse to provide emergency contraceptive care to rape victims if they objected due to a [[religious belief]]. After the amendment failed, Brown did vote for the main bill which, along with other patient rights, requires healthcare workers and hospitals to provide such care.<ref name="daughters">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/01/coakley_campaig_1.html |title=Brown's daughters call for Coakley to take down ad |date=January 12, 2010 |first=Matt|last=Viser |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Coakley's ad featured a male voice that said, "Brown even favors letting hospitals deny emergency contraception to rape victims," over the ad's graphic which had the words, "Deny care to rape victims."<ref name="daughters" /> Brown's daughter [[Ayla Brown|Ayla]] called the Coakley ad "completely inaccurate and misleading", and stated that her father would never deny care to a rape victim.  Brown criticized Coakley for running what he described as attack ads.<ref name="daughters" />

In the 2010 Senate race, although Brown was not endorsed by the Greater Boston Tea Party group,<ref>The GBTP website states: "Please note that while a few Tea Party groups across the nation have endorsed either Brown or Kennedy, the Greater Boston Tea Party has not endorsed either. We are encouraging you to get informed, make your own decision and then get involved."{{cite web|url=http://greaterbostonteaparty.com/2010/01/massachusetts-special-senate-election-update/ |title=Massachusetts Special Senate Election Update|date=January 7, 2010|author=C Varley|work=What's Brewing|publisher=Greater Boston Tea Party}}</ref> the group organized a fund-raising breakfast for him in Boston.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brown campaign website notice|url=http://www.brownforussenate.com/event/2010-01-02/friends-tea-party-scott-brown-reception|title=Friends of the Tea Party Scott Brown Reception|publisher=Scott Brown for United States Senate|date=January 2, 2010}}</ref> The Tea Party Express also endorsed Brown<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=American Conservative Daily|date=January 9, 2010| url=http://www.americanconservativedaily.com/2010/01/tea-party-express-endorses-scott-brown-for-u-s-senate-massachusetts/ |title=Tea Party Express Endorses Scott Brown for US Senate Massachusetts}}</ref> and bought ads on the national cable networks supporting Brown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teapartyexpressblog.blogspot.com/ |title=Scott Brown Campaign: Shhh!!! A secret we can now share with you all!|date=January 18, 2010|publisher=Tea Party Express}}</ref>

When told that at various times he has been labeled a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]], [[moderate]] and a [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] Republican, he responded "I'm a Scott Brown Republican."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theplumline.whorunsgov.com/scott-brown-transcript/ |title=Scott Brown Transcript|work=Greg Sergant's Blog|date=Undated|publisher=The Plum Line}}</ref> According to Politifact, while Brown was a Massachusetts legislator, he voted about 90 percent with the state Republican leadership;<ref>{{cite web|work=Politifact|url= http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2010/jan/18/barack-obama/obama-says-browns-voting-record-not-independent/ |date=January 18, 2010|title=Obama says Brown's voting record is not that of an independent}}</ref> however, Republican Leadership in the Massachusetts legislature is generally considered far more moderate than the national Republican Party.<ref>{{cite web|work=Boris Shor|url= http://bshor.wordpress.com/2010/01/15/scott-brown-is-a-more-liberal-republican-than-dede-scozzafava/ |date= January 15, 2010|title=Scott Brown is a more Liberal Republican than Dede Scozzafava}}</ref>

On election night, after Coakley conceded, Brown gave a victory speech that concluded, "I'm Scott Brown, I'm from Wrentham, I drive a truck, and I am nobody's senator but yours."<ref>{{cite news|title=Scott Brown's Victory Speech|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/20/us/politics/20text-brown.html?pagewanted=all|first=Scott|last=Brown|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2010}}</ref>

===Tenure===
Brown was sworn in to office on February 4, 2010, by [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]], in his capacity as [[President of the Senate]], on the floor of the Senate.<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/02/04/Brown-sworn-in-to-fill-Kennedy-Senate-seat/UPI-82741265303270/ "Brown sworn in to fill Kennedy Senate seat"], UPI. February 4, 2010.</ref>  As a [[Classes of United States Senators#Class_I|Class I]] Senator, his term will last until January 3, 2013.

Brown was among the speakers at the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[Washington, D.C.]], introducing former Massachusetts [[governor of Massachusetts|governor]] [[Mitt Romney]].<ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/blogs/beltway-confidential/Scott-Brown-surprise-at-CPAC-84720617.html "Sen. Scott Brown surprise at CPAC"], The Washington Examiner. February 18, 2010.</ref> Despite his appearance at CPAC, where he alluded to his election as making "big government spenders...[not] feel good at all", Brown refused to rule out a vote for a Democratic "jobs bill" proposal, and has praised both [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Harry Reid]] of [[Nevada]] and [[seniority in the United States Senate|senior]] Senator [[John Kerry]] of [[Massachusetts]] for indicating their willingness to work with him across party lines.<ref>
{{cite news
| url = http://news.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view/20100220scott_brown_calls_relations_with_john_kerry_surprisingly_positive/
| title = Scott Brown calls relations with John Kerry 'surprisingly positive'
| work = [[Boston Herald]]
| author = Jim O'Sullivan
| agency = State House News Service
| date = February 20, 2010
}}
<!-- also at http://news.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view.bg?articleid=1234223 -->
</ref> Scott was one of five Republican senators to vote for [[cloture]] on the [[Hiring Incentives to Restore Employment Act|jobs bill]]. The motion passed in the Senate 62<U+2013>30 on February 22, 2010.<ref>{{Citation  | last = Oliphant  | first = James  | last2 = Hook  | first2 = Janet  | title = Democrats block filibuster on scaled-back jobs bill  | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]  | date = 2010-02-23
  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2010/feb/23/nation/la-na-jobs-vote23-2010feb23  | accessdate = 2010-03-04}}</ref> In an [[up or down vote]] on the bill itself on February 24, 2010, Brown voted for final passage, helping to pass the bill 70-28.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2010/02/24/2211029.aspx |title=Jobs bill passes overwhelmingly |work=First Read |publisher=[[msnbc.com]] |date=February 24, 2010}}</ref>

