==Political positions==
[[File:Barack Obama with Scott Brown.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Brown meets [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] in the [[Oval Office]], June 2010.]]
Brown has positioned himself as a [[American conservative|conservative]] counterweight to Massachusetts' previously all-Democratic, 12-member congressional delegation.<ref name="live" /><ref name="dog" /> He describes himself as socially moderate and fiscally conservative. He identifies himself as a "[[Reagan Republican]]". He has said, "I'm going to be the only person down there who is going to be the independent voter and thinker... I've always been the underdog in one shape or form."<ref name="dog" />

===Fiscal policy===
Brown opposes a proposed multi-billion dollar tax on banks to recoup bailout money and prescribing of bank executive compensation. Brown, discussing the proposal through a spokesperson, said that he is "opposed to higher taxes, especially in the midst of a [[recession of 2008|severe recession]]". He also opposes it on the grounds that the tax would likely be passed onto consumers in the form of higher service and [[Automated teller machine|ATM]] fees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/01/brown_criticize.html|title=Mass. Senate candidates clash on terrorism, bank bailout tax|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=January 14, 2010|author1=Stephanie Ebbert|author2=Matt Viser|accessdate=January 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/news/national-politics/story/1784255.html|title=Mass. Senate candidate Brown bashes Obama bank tax|date=January 16, 2010|first=Beth|last=Fouhy|accessdate=January 17, 2010|publisher=[[The Fresno Bee]]}}</ref> In September 2010, Brown opposed a Senate bill creating a $30 billion government fund aimed at encouraging lending to small businesses. The bill combines the fund with $12 billion in new tax breaks. Brown criticized the bill for including a provision much like [[Troubled Asset Relief Program|TARP]], stating: "Banks making lending decisions with government funds is not the way to get our economy moving again.<U+2019><U+2019><ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2010/09/15/senate_oks_tax_breaks_for_small_businesses/ Small-business tax breaks clear a hurdle in the Senate 'Brown decries plan, calling it a new bailout; End of filibuster a win for Obama']. September 15, 2010</ref>

On December 12, 2010, the ''[[Boston Globe]]'' reported that "[c]ampaign contributions to [Brown] from the financial industry spiked sharply during a critical three-week period last summer as the fate of the [[Dodd<U+2013>Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Wall Street regulatory overhaul]] hung in the balance and Brown used the leverage of his swing vote to win key concessions sought by firms."<ref name="Globe">Slack, Donovan (2010-12-12) [http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2010/12/12/banks_donations_soared_as_brown_negotiated/?page=full Donations poured in as Brown<U+2019>s role grew], ''[[Boston Globe]]''</ref> Brown received more than ten times the amount of contributions from the [[financial services industry]] as [[House Financial Services Committee]] chairman (and author of the legislation) [[Barney Frank]] during the same period.<ref name="Globe" /> According to the ''[[Boston Globe|Globe]]'':

<blockquote>
Brown<U+2019>s efforts benefited large Massachusetts companies such as [[MassMutual Financial Group]], [[Liberty Mutual Insurance]], [[Fidelity Investments]], and [[State Street Corporation|State Street Corp.]], whose executives and [[political action committee]]s contributed $29,000 to Brown during the three-week period he was extracting the concessions from Democrats.

They also benefited major out-of-state institutions such as [[Goldman Sachs]], [[UBS]], and [[JPMorgan Chase]]. Those and other out-of-state financial interests gave Brown a total of $50,000 during the period.<ref name="Globe" />
</blockquote>

===Foreign policy===
Brown supports President Barack Obama's decision to send 30,000 more troops to [[War in Afghanistan (2001<U+2013>present)|fight in Afghanistan]]. He cited [[Stanley McChrystal]]'s recommendations as a reason for his support.<ref name="live" /> He also advocates that suspected [[terrorist]]s be tried in [[military tribunal]]s and not civilian courts.<ref name="key" /> He also supports the limited use of "[[enhanced interrogation techniques]]", including [[waterboarding]] against non-citizen terrorist suspects.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brown and Coakley clash over terror suspects' rights|date=January 5, 2010|accessdate=January 19, 2010|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/05/brown_coakley_clash_over_suspected_terrorists_rights/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]] | first=Brian C. | last=Mooney}}</ref> He supports a [[two-state solution]] for the [[Israel-Palestinian conflict]] in which Israel and a new, independent [[Palestinian state]] would co-exist side by side.<ref name="caller" />

===Veteran services===
In 2007, Brown wrote a law establishing a check off box on State income tax forms to allow a filer to indicate if he or she is a veteran of the [[Iraq War|Iraq]] or [[Afghanistan]] wars. The measure's purpose is to locate and inform returning veterans of benefits they qualify for.  Known as the "Welcome Home" bonus, it was passed with [[bipartisan]] support.<ref name="bio" />  Brown also amended the [[Dodd<U+2013>Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]], with Senator [[Jack Reed (politician)|Jack Reed]] ([[Rhode Island|RI]]), to create a dedicated military liaison office within the newly formed [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]], which aside from defending against unscrupulous lenders, also ensures protection of military families against fraudulent life insurance policies.  The measure passed the [[U.S. Senate]] 99 to 1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&docid=f:h4173enr.txt.pdf |title=H.R. 4173 (111th Congress) |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]]}}</ref>

===Health care===
Brown supported the 2006 [[Massachusetts health care reform]], which requires all residents to have [[health insurance]], with a state-subsidized plan created for those who cannot afford to insure themselves. Brown does not support President Obama's health care reform plan in its current form as approved by the Democratic-led House and Senate.  He has stated this plan is fiscally unsound, and during his campaign notably pledged to be the 41st vote to [[filibuster]] the bill in the Senate.<ref>{{cite news
| author = Browenstein, Joseph
| url = http://abcnews.go.com/Health/HealthCare/scott-brown-win-massachusetts-begs-question-health-care/story?id=9615918
| title = Health Care Overhaul's Uncertain, Super-Majority-Free Future
| work = [[ABC News]]
| date = January 21, 2010
}}</ref>

Brown voted for a state measure on patients' rights that, among other provisions, requires emergency rooms to provide what is known as the [[emergency contraception|morning-after pill]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Wellness/morning-pill-spurs-abortion-controversy/story?id=9700748 |title=Pregnancy Prevention or Abortion? New Emergency Contraception Pill Walks the Line |work=[[ABC News]] |date=February 1, 2010 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> to rape victims to prevent an unwanted pregnancy from developing.  In consideration of health care workers who might have a religious objection to administering this medication, Brown attached what became known as the Conscientious Objector amendment which would have exempted these workers, as well as religious hospitals, from being required to provide this medication.  However, Brown's amendment also required that all hospitals still had to provide a means for the patient to receive the medication, either by providing another healthcare worker willing to administer the medication, or, in the case of religious hospitals, to provide transportation to another facility, and in a timely manner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jan/24/nation/la-na-scott-brown24-2010jan24 |title=What makes Scott Brown run? |author=Kathleen Hennessey |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2010-01-24 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref>  The amendment did not pass.<ref name="Estes">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/06/in_debate_senate_candidates_seek_to_define_differences/?page=full |title=In debate, Senate candidates seek to define differences |author=Andrea Estes |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2010-01-06 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> Brown remains in favor of allowing religious hospitals to refuse to provide emergency contraception on moral or religious grounds, as he stated in the January 5, 2010 candidate debate.<ref name="Estes" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.969bostontalks.com/Podcasts/1466/010510senatedebatepart1.mp3 |title=96.9 Boston Talks podcast of the January 5, 2010 debate |date= |accessdate=2010-07-05}}</ref>

===Energy policy===
He supports expanding [[solar power|solar]], [[wind power|wind]], and [[nuclear power]], and [[offshore drilling]] exploration as a means to reduce the country's dependence on foreign oil.<ref name="dog" /> Although, when faced with the controversial issue of whether an [[Cape Wind|offshore wind farm]] should be allowed in the waters off the Cape Cod coast in Massachusetts, a major tourist destination and boating location, he expressed opposition due to the fact he believed it would hinder tourism and boating in the area.<ref>{{cite news |author=Seelye, K. Q. |date=April 28, 2010 |title=Regulators Approve First Offshore Wind Farm in U.S. |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 28, 2010 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/29/us/29wind.html?hp}}</ref>

===Social issues===
Brown refers to the currently legalized [[same-sex marriage in Massachusetts]] as a settled issue, which he does not wish to change.<ref name="live" /> Brown has said he personally believes marriage is between a man and a woman, but would oppose a constitutional amendment banning [[gay marriage]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hook |first=Janet |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-na-scott-brown22-2010jan22,0,1805237.story |title=Scott Brown gets a hero's welcome from Senate Republicans |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2010-01-22 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> He is in favor of [[Civil union in the United States|civil unions]].<ref name="dog" /> He opposes ending the [[Defense of Marriage Act]], but otherwise favors leaving the issue to the states to decide.<ref name="parker" /> After initially claiming neutrality on "[[don't ask, don't tell]]", the ban on openly gay military personnel,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/2010/01/31/brown-dadt/ |title=Will Scott Brown support repealing Don't Ask, Don't Tell? |work=Think Progress |date=January 31, 2010}}</ref> he joined a handful of Republicans who broke with their party to repeal the ban in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/politics/view/20101203scott_brown_ill_back_repeal_of_military_gay_ban/ |title=Scott Brown: I'll back repeal of military gay ban |work=[[The Boston Herald]] |date=December 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed |title='Don't ask, don't tell' is repealed by Senate; bill awaits Obama's signing|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/18/AR2010121801729_2.html?sid=ST2010121803394|accessdate=2011-01-02|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=19 December 2010}}</ref>

Brown has supported a presumption of shared parenting after divorce and was a co-sponsor of Fathers and Families HB 1460.<ref name="ontheissues1">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/senate/Scott_Brown.htm |title=Scott Brown on the Issues |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date= |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref>

Brown has stated that ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' is settled law. He is against [[intact dilation and evacuation|intact dilation and evacuation abortions]] (known by opponents as "partial birth abortion") and has spoken in favor of [[parental consent]]<ref name="dog" /> for minors who seek an abortion. He said he would not use abortion as a [[litmus test (politics)|litmus test]] in [[Appointment and confirmation to the Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court confirmations]].<ref name="dog" /> He opposes federal funding for [[elective abortion]] in accordance with the [[Hyde Amendment]].<ref name="parker" />

===Crime and security===
Brown supports strengthening Massachusetts sex offender penalties.<ref name="ontheissues1" /> He also supports the [[death penalty]].<ref name="caller">{{cite news|publisher=The Daily Caller|title=Where Senator-elect Scott Brown stands on issues&nbsp;<U+2014> other than health care|first=Alex|last=Pappas|date=January 19, 2010|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> He supports the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|right to bear arms]], with some restrictions such as licenses and background checks.<ref name="ontheissues1" /> He opposes providing [[driver's licenses]] and in-state tuition to [[illegal immigrant]]s. He also supports strengthening border enforcement and creating an employment verification system with penalties for companies that hire illegal immigrants.<ref name="caller" />

==Organizational associations and honors==
{{Rquote|right|Scott Brown had a profound impact on national politics in the last year. His surprise victory upended conventional wisdom, inspired a legion of long-shot challenges, and energized Republicans and Democrats alike. Brown<U+2019>s election showed the country that anything is possible, that no seat or incumbent is safe from challenge. And his maneuvering once in office produced the tiniest rays of bipartisanship in a Senate dark with dysfunction. For all of these reasons, he is our 2010 Bostonian of the Year.|Neil Swidey, ''[[The Boston Globe]]'<ref name="Bostonian of the Year" />}}
Brown is a 30-year member of the [[Massachusetts National Guard]], in which he currently holds the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps]]. Brown was awarded the [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]] for meritorious service in organizing the National Guard to quickly support [[homeland security]] following the terrorist attacks of [[September 11, 2001]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/wakefield/local_news/x1595355833|title=Wakefield son promoted to lieutenant colonel|last=Band|first=Gary|date=31 January 2007|work=The Wakfield Observer|accessdate=2 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scott-brown.us/ |title=Senator Scott Brown Army Commendation Medal}}</ref> He has also completed [[United States Army Airborne School|Airborne School]] and been awarded the [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]].<ref name="bio" />

Brown has received the Public Servant of the Year Award from the United Chamber of Commerce for his leadership in reforming the state's [[sex offender]] laws and protecting [[victims' rights]].<ref>Suddath, Claire. [http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1954918,00.html "2-Minute Bio: Scott Brown"] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' January 19, 2010.</ref> Brown's family has helped raise funds for such [[non-profit organizations]] as Horace Mann Educational Associates (HMEA,Inc.), Wrentham Developmental Center, Charles River Arc, and the Arc of Northern Bristol County, all for the care and support of those with [[developmental disabilities]]. He has also been recognized by the [[National Federation of Independent Businesses]] (NFIB) for his work in creating an environment that encourages job growth and expansion in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfib.com/nfib-in-my-state/nfib-in-my-state-content/cmsid/50397/ |title=In My State: Massachusetts U.S. Senate Special Election News |publisher=[[National Federation of Independent Businesses|NFIB]]}}</ref> The ''[[Boston Globe]]'' selected Brown as the 2010 Bostonian of the Year, citing his "profound impact on national politics in the last year".<ref name="Bostonian of the Year">{{cite news|last=Swidey|first=Neil|title=The Life of the party: Scott Brown|url=http://www.boston.com/lifestyle/articles/2011/01/02/the_life_of_the_party_scott_brown/?page=1|accessdate=4 January 2011|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=2 January 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Family===
Brown is married to former [[WCVB-TV]] reporter [[Gail Huff]], whom he met through modeling. They have two daughters, [[Ayla Brown|Ayla]], an ''[[American Idol]]'' semi-finalist and a student at [[Boston College]], and Arianna, a competitive equestrian and pre-medical student at [[Syracuse University]].<ref name="bruni20100228">
{{cite news
| url = http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/28/magazine/28Brown-t.html?pagewanted=all
| title = Where Scott Brown Is Coming From
| author = Frank Bruni
| work = [[The New York Times]]
| date = February 22, 2010
}}</ref> Besides their primary home in [[Massachusetts]], the couple owns a home in [[Rye, New Hampshire]], three rental condos in [[Boston]], and a timeshare on the Caribbean island of [[Aruba]].<ref name="dog" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Financial disclosure, April 2009|publisher= Mass State Ethics commission|url=http://www.massinc.org/fileadmin/CommonWealth/Disclosure_forms/Senate/Brown_Scott_P.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>
{{cite news
| url = http://news.bostonherald.com/news/politics/view/20100122compared_to_colleagues_scott_brown_lacks_green/
| title = Compared to colleagues, Scott Brown lacks green
| author = Laura Crimaldi
| work = [[Boston Herald]]
| date = January 22, 2010
}}</ref>

===Religion===
Brown and his family are members of the [[Christian Reformed Church in North America]]. They worship at New England Chapel in [[Franklin, Massachusetts]]. They also have a relationship with a community of [[Cistercian]]s, more commonly known as [[Trappists|Trappistine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abbey.msmabbey.org/ |title=Welcome to Mount Saint Mary's Abbey
 |publisher=Mount Saint Mary's Abbey |date=2010-02-24 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abbey.msmabbey.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1%3Awelcome&catid=13%3Aabbey&Itemid=60&lang=en&limitstart=1 |title=Monastic Life - Page 2 |publisher=Mount Saint Mary's Abbey |date=2010-02-24 |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> [[Roman Catholic]] nuns at Mount St. Mary's Abbey in [[Wrentham, Massachusetts]]. The Brown family has raised over $5 million for the order, helping to install [[solar panels]], a [[wind turbine]] and a candy manufacturing plant that the order operates.<ref name="dog" />

